==English==

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[glæm]]''

===Pronunciation===
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-iːm|-iːm]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[small]] or indistinct [[shaft]] or stream of [[light]].
#:''He could see the '''gleams''' of the searchers' flashlights from across the moor.''
# A [[glimpse]] or [[hint]]; an [[indistinct]] [[sign]] of something.
#:''Even though the miners had been trapped in the shaft for days, the rescue workers preserved a '''gleam''' of optimism that they might still survive.''
# [[brightness|Brightness]] or [[shininess]]; [[splendor]].
#:''The '''gleam''' from the spokesmodel's teeth was blinding.''

====Synonyms====
*(''small shaft or stream of light''): [[beam]], [[ray]]
*(''glimpse or indistinct sign''): [[flicker]], [[glimmer]], [[trace]] 
*(''brightness or splendor''): [[dazzle]], [[lambency]], [[shine]]

